The biggest flaw of the Simple Builder is that it cannot enforce required parameters at compile-time. 
A developer could accidentally call .build() without setting a mandatory field, causing a runtime crash.

The Step Builder solves this by forcing the developer through a strict sequence of steps using interfaces.

How it works: Each configuration step returns a different interface that only contains the method for the next step.
You literally cannot call .build() until you have navigated through all the required interfaces.

The Goal: Compile-time safety. Guiding the developer step-by-step so they cannot possibly build an invalid object.

The Vibe: "An installation wizard. You cannot click 'Next' until you fill out the current page."

You have strict required parameters and want the compiler to enforce the configuration order.
Returns interfaces instead of the builder itself.
